# Function Comments

Add a brief comment above a function when its role isn't immediately obvious from the signature alone. Skip it when the function is short enough that the body says everything.

## The comment must explain _why_ the function is called, not _what_ it does

A comment that rephrases the body in prose adds no value and must not be used.

```ws
// ❌ BAD — restates the code
// Checks if lightRewriteSettings is null, creates it if so, then returns it.
public function GetLightRewriteSettings() : CLightRewriteSettings { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — explains the impetus / caller contract
// Gets the LightRewrite settings singleton - lazy initialised
public function GetLightRewriteSettings() : CLightRewriteSettings { ... }
```

```ws
// ❌ BAD — restates the code
// Calls wrappedMethod then calls OptionValueChanged on lightRewriteSettings.
function OnOptionValueChanged(...) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — explains why this wrapper exists
// Forward every option-change event to the settings object for filtering.
function OnOptionValueChanged(...) { ... }
```

## When to omit a comment entirely

Omit when the function name + signature make the purpose self-evident:

```ws
// No comment needed — name is the full explanation
public function IsEnabled() : bool { return isEnabled; }
```

## Style

- One line is almost always enough; two lines at most.
- Write in plain English, imperative or declarative — no full stops required.
